I"E<p><img src="/assets/img/cppdaily/cpp-daily-episode8.jpg" alt="Boolean Logics with STL" /></p>

<p>Logic gates or circuits are devices that operate and work with one or more logic input signals to produce one and only one output, depending on the function implemented in the circuit.</p>

<p>The situations ‚ÄúTruth‚Äù and ‚ÄúFalse‚Äù are studied in the Mathematical Logic or Boole Logic. There are the following logic gates: AND, OR and NOT are the main ones, because with them we can form the others that are: NAND, NOR, XOR and XNOR.</p>

<p>Remembering that when analyzing execution output: 0 is true (without error) and 1 is false ( &gt;= 1 is error ), so this can confuse your mind when analyzing the examples, as it is the other way around, but I will not invert because it is as soon as it is in reality, then we will use the concept of computation and not execution output: 0 as false and 1 is true. üòÉ</p>

